Fix Hadrian to recognize MinGW-w64 platform vendor string

Windows does not support -dynamic-too, so shared libraries cannot be built.
The platformSupportsSharedLibs check needs to recognize both "unknown" vendor
(traditional GHC builds) and "w64" vendor (MinGW-w64 toolchain used by conda-forge).

Without this fix, the MinGW-w64 platform string "x86_64-w64-mingw32" is not
recognized as a "bad platform" for shared libs, causing Hadrian to request
dynamic RTS builds (like threadedLoggingDynamic) that fail because Windows
cannot build .dll files without -dynamic-too support.

--- a/hadrian/src/Oracles/Flag.hs
+++ b/hadrian/src/Oracles/Flag.hs
@@ -62,7 +62,10 @@
 platformSupportsSharedLibs = do
     badPlatform   <- anyTargetPlatform [ "powerpc-unknown-linux"
                                        , "x86_64-unknown-mingw32"
-                                       , "i386-unknown-mingw32" ]
+                                       , "x86_64-w64-mingw32"
+                                       , "i686-w64-mingw32"
+                                       , "i386-unknown-mingw32"
+                                       , "i386-w64-mingw32" ]
     solaris       <- anyTargetPlatform [ "i386-unknown-solaris2" ]
     solarisBroken <- flag SolarisBrokenShld
     return $ not (badPlatform || solaris && solarisBroken)
